WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.009 --> 00:00:03.130
Distinguishing risk from emotional communication,

1
00:00:03.609 --> 00:00:05.530
seeing what's really going on.

2
00:00:06.739 --> 00:00:08.199
You may have seen this.

3
00:00:08.579 --> 00:00:10.729
A young person becomes aggressive.

4
00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:12.020
They walk out,

5
00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:13.880
they refuse to engage,

6
00:00:14.229 --> 00:00:15.399
and straightway

7
00:00:15.619 --> 00:00:17.280
the focus goes to risk.

8
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.500
This needs managing.

9
00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:21.200
This needs stopping.

10
00:00:22.299 --> 00:00:23.569
And sometimes,

11
00:00:24.139 --> 00:00:25.440
that's absolutely right.

12
00:00:25.870 --> 00:00:27.149
But let me ask you something.

13
00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:30.739
What if that behavior is also telling you something,

14
00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:34.080
because one of the biggest challenges in this profession

15
00:00:34.659 --> 00:00:38.139
is knowing the difference between behavior that presents risk

16
00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:41.259
and behavior that is communicating distress.

17
00:00:41.979 --> 00:00:43.150
And the truth is,

18
00:00:43.619 --> 00:00:45.459
they often look exactly the same.

19
00:00:46.349 --> 00:00:48.750
A young person storms out of the room.

20
00:00:49.549 --> 00:00:51.110
Is that risky behavior?

21
00:00:51.819 --> 00:00:53.400
Or are they overwhelmed

22
00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:54.599
and trying to cope?

23
00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:57.669
Someone becomes verbally aggressive.

24
00:00:58.209 --> 00:00:59.549
Is that a safety concern

25
00:01:00.209 --> 00:01:02.290
or a response to feeling threatened?

26
00:01:03.330 --> 00:01:04.870
What's really going on here

27
00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:07.510
is that behavior can be two things at once.

28
00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:09.300
It can be unsafe,

29
00:01:09.699 --> 00:01:11.209
and it can be communication,

30
00:01:11.449 --> 00:01:13.790
and this is where we sometimes get it wrong.

31
00:01:14.169 --> 00:01:16.160
We go straight into control mode.

32
00:01:16.489 --> 00:01:18.550
We focus on stopping the behavior,

33
00:01:18.730 --> 00:01:20.160
enforcing boundaries,

34
00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:21.809
managing the situation.

35
00:01:22.569 --> 00:01:23.470
And again,

36
00:01:24.089 --> 00:01:25.330
sometimes that's necessary.

37
00:01:26.230 --> 00:01:27.839
But if that's all we do,

38
00:01:28.239 --> 00:01:29.760
we miss what's driving it.

39
00:01:30.739 --> 00:01:33.040
Behavior is often communication.

40
00:01:33.379 --> 00:01:35.800
There is usually a reason behind the behavior,

41
00:01:36.339 --> 00:01:38.339
and if we don't understand that reason,

42
00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:40.500
the behavior is likely to repeat.

43
00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:45.919
What this means in practice is holding both things in mind at the same time.

44
00:01:47.050 --> 00:01:47.690
First,

45
00:01:48.290 --> 00:01:50.129
is anyone at risk right now?

46
00:01:50.489 --> 00:01:51.809
If the answer is yes,

47
00:01:52.089 --> 00:01:53.569
safety comes first,

48
00:01:53.809 --> 00:01:54.559
always.

49
00:01:55.309 --> 00:01:56.550
But alongside that,

50
00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:57.779
we also ask,

51
00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:00.319
what might this behavior be telling me?

52
00:02:00.919 --> 00:02:00.930
Because

53
00:02:01.309 --> 00:02:03.419
if we only respond to the risk,

54
00:02:03.959 --> 00:02:05.610
we manage the moment

55
00:02:05.919 --> 00:02:07.830
if we understand the communication.

56
00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:09.578
We change the pattern.

57
00:02:10.899 --> 00:02:14.630
Think about a time when you felt overwhelmed or misunderstood.

58
00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:16.960
If someone came in strong,

59
00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:18.070
raised voice,

60
00:02:18.529 --> 00:02:18.919
pressure,

61
00:02:19.289 --> 00:02:19.830
control.

62
00:02:20.559 --> 00:02:22.020
It probably didn't help.

63
00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:24.419
It may even have made things worse.

64
00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:25.970
It's no different here.

65
00:02:26.270 --> 00:02:27.779
For the people we support,

66
00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:29.619
especially those with trauma,

67
00:02:30.119 --> 00:02:32.880
strong adult responses can feel like threat.

68
00:02:33.589 --> 00:02:35.289
That's when we see escalation,

69
00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:36.270
fight,

70
00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:36.889
flight,

71
00:02:37.470 --> 00:02:37.990
freeze.

72
00:02:38.789 --> 00:02:41.250
Not because they're choosing to make things harder,

73
00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:43.729
but because they feel unsafe.

74
00:02:44.750 --> 00:02:46.729
So what does good practice look like?

75
00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:49.610
It means setting clear boundaries when needed,

76
00:02:50.029 --> 00:02:51.389
but doing it in a calm,

77
00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:52.710
measured way.

78
00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:54.970
It means not ignoring risk,

79
00:02:55.509 --> 00:02:58.669
but also not losing sight of the person behind the behavior.

80
00:02:59.339 --> 00:03:01.139
It means being able to pause,

81
00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:02.259
even briefly,

82
00:03:02.509 --> 00:03:03.179
and think.

83
00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.080
What's happening here underneath this?

84
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:07.009
Because

85
00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:09.750
this is where safeguarding really sits,

86
00:03:10.119 --> 00:03:12.100
not just in reacting to behavior,

87
00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:13.880
but in understanding it.

88
00:03:14.619 --> 00:03:16.649
And when we get that balance right,

89
00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:18.759
we reduce escalation,

90
00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:20.289
we build trust,

91
00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:23.520
and we respond in a way that actually makes a difference.